title: For Sale:  WPA PSU 1x/4x Scope - $500.00
postcontent: WTS/T Wolf NBZ PSU 1x/4x Variable Zoom ScopeScope is crystal clear and built like a tank(has 556 reticle with range finder and bullet drop compensator).  Picatinny rail mounts are built into the optic which is a nice feature.  Glass is super clear SCHOTT.  I really like this scope but I want to sell/trade it in order to get a Eotech/Aimpoint, dont really need the magnifacion with the rifle its on.Intersted in any Eotech (with buttons on side models) or aimpoints.  Writeup from website below:The NPZ PSU 1x/4x switchable zoom optical gun sight is the only switchable zoom prism sight alternative to the famous ELCAN Specter DR 1x/4x dual role combat sight. In our opinion, it is also every bit the sight that the ELCAN is while coming in at $900 less. Both the PSU and the ELCAN Specter DR use an internal 4x power magnifier at the front to cancel out the fixed 4x prism sight located at the rear part of both sights. The difference is that the ELCAN uses a rotating prism design for its built-in magnifier while the PSU has a sliding conventional lens in its magnifier part. Another big difference is that the PSU uses a common internal adjustment system, while the ELCAN has a non-standard and for many, unpopular, external adjustment setup. The PSU 1x/4x uses German SCHOTT glass for its lens and prism. SCHOTT optical glass is the best in the world and found only in the finest, high-end optics. When set to 1x magnification, the PSU provides a huge 26 degree field of view for rapid, both-eyes-open target engagement. When the magnification switch is flipped to 4x, the sight’s reticle is extended for range-finding out to 800 meters and comes in with a field of view a full degree wider than the ELCAN. The PSU is manufactured from a solid aluminum alloy body and is shockproof and watertight. The fully multi-coated optics are sharp and bright with accurate color rendition and excellent resolution. The PSU comes with a Mil-Dot style reticle or a BDC reticle. The BDC reticle provides ballistic compensation out to 800 meters and has a telemetric rangefinder in the lower right that provides height-based range-finding for a man-sized 1.8 meter target. The BDC is calibrated for the 62 grain M855 NATO round. The PSU’s reticle is illuminated by a single common CR2032 lithium battery and the illumination is not daylight visible but for use in dusk conditions. A definite BEST CHOICE! Compare the PSU to the ELCAN and you'll find the performance equal or better at a significantly lower price.

title: For Sale:  PSL Dragunov
postcontent:
Package includes, Rifle, original pouch, 2 mags, cleaning kit, scope, and scope cover.  Factory built and imported, not a kit.
The PSL is chambered for the same venerable 7.62x56R (rimmed) cartridge as the Dragunov, and feeds from a ten-round detachable mag. The magazine used on the PSL differs from that of Dragunov models in that it is stamped with an X shaped pattern on the side, rather than the waffle style stamp found on the Russian and Chinese magazines. The magazines, though they are similar in shape and size, are not interchangeable between the Dragunov and PSL without modification.
The PSL has been in service in Romania since the 1970s and is widely sold on the world market. They are frequently encountered in Iraq where they appear to be quite popular. The simplicity of the rifle makes it ideal for soldiers to use and maintain. The action, being a variant of the AKM's, is extremely reliable despite lack of maintenance, and is particularly forgiving of sand and other debris. The scope's reticle pattern is easy to use and makes range estimation quick and reasonably accurate without any mathematical calculations necessary. With some simple instruction an average individual can be issued a PSL and successfully engage targets at ranges that far exceed the accurate capabilities of non-scoped assault rifles like the AKM, AK-47, etc. Accuracy varies greatly, however, between individual rifles to a greater extent to other rifles in its class, probably due to insufficient quality control during the manufacturing process. In the hands of a capable shooter and with quality ammunition such as 7N1 and 7N14 a PSL is capable of 1 MOA (approximately 1" at 100 yards) or less while the rifles on the other end of the spectrum are only capable of about 3 MOA.
